<section class="mbr-section mbr-section--relative mbr-section--fixed-size" id="msg-box3-46" style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    
    <div class="mbr-section__container container mbr-section__container--first" style="padding-top: 124px;">
        <div class="mbr-header mbr-header--wysiwyg row">
            <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1">
                <h4 class="mbr-header__text"><span style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: normal;">“I want to do something splendid…
Something heroic or wonderful that won’t be forgotten after I’m dead...<br>
I think I shall write books.” 
― Louisa May Alcott
</span>
</h4>
                
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
	<div class="mbr-section__container mbr-section__container--center mbr-section__container--middle">
                    <figure class="mbr-figure"><img src="assets/images/blog_1.jpg" class="mbr-figure__img"></figure>
                </div>
    <div class="mbr-section__container container mbr-section__container--last" style="padding-bottom: 93px;">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="mbr-article mbr-article--wysiwyg col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1"><h2><br/><br/><br/>
			Writing a novel may not be a easy task, it is a long process requiring immense planning and thinking. So if you are planning to write a novel, as you can imagine, it is going to take more planning and thinking than ever.
So here are some tips that will help you write a novel:

			</h2>			
			</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="mbr-section__container container mbr-section__container--last" style="padding-bottom: 93px;">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="mbr-article mbr-article--wysiwyg col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1">
			<ol style="font-size: 20px; color : Black">
			<li><h1>Write the story you’d most want to read:</h1><br/> Don’t write a story just because you think it might be a bestseller. Think about the books you love, the ones you really lose yourself in. If those are mysteries, then don’t try to write an historical romance or a quiet literary novel. It might not be anything genre-specific that you love, but a certain voice, or type of story, or kinds of characters. Write what you love. Do me a favour — right now, today, start a list of all your crazy obsessions, the things that get your heart pumping, that wake you up in the middle of the night. Put it above your desk and use it to guide you, to jumpstart your writing each and every day.</li>
			<br/><li><h1>Begin with character: </h1><br/> Choosing up a character is important task, your character must be strong, unique, poignant, and well-defined. Your characters should be so well-developed in your mind that it feels natural to help them navigate your fictional world.  </li>
			<br/><li><h1>Start writing and set goals:</h1><br/> Start writing your novel, set up of your goals like you have to write a page or two or may be a chapter daily and make it happen. Build habit of writing daily and stop making excuses to yourself.  </li>
			<br/><li><h1>Stick with it the project: </h1><br/> You’ll be tempted to give up a thousand and one times. Don’t. Finish the story. Then work twice as hard to revise it. Do your best to get it out in the world. It’s your dream, so give it a chance to happen. If your first book has enough potential you never know it can be a bestseller.  </li>
			</div></div>
        </div>
    
     <div class="mbr-section__container container mbr-section__container--first" style="padding-top: 124px; ">
      
            <div class="col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1">
                <h4 style="font-size: 28px; color : black;">
	                   Some famous first novels that became best seller:<br/><br/>
				</h4>
				<ul style="font-size: 20px;">
					   <li>Emily Brontë's Wuthering Heights</li><br/>
					   <li>Ian Caldwell and Dustin Thomason's The Rule of Four </li><br/>
					   <li>Agatha Christie's The Mysterious Affair at Styles </li><br/>
					   <li>Ralph Ellison's only novel Invisible Man </li><br/>
					   <li>Janet Fitch's White Oleander </li><br/>
					   <li>F. Scott Fitzgerald's This Side of Paradis </li><br/>
					   <li>Chetan Bhagat's Five Point Someone </li><br/>
					   <li>Ravinder Singh's I too had a Love Story </li><br/>
					   <li>Salman Rushdie's Grimus </li><br/>
					   </ul>
               <h2>And many more...So start writing your book</h2><br/><br/>
			</div></div>
   </section>

